  "etymology": {
    "text": "Via Latin furca (fork, pitchfork), the word appears in Old English as *furkō/force for a forked instrument (attested c. 9th–11th century) and then Middle English forke; later forms were reinforced by Latin-derived forms such as furcate/forque. The ultimate origin is uncertain: some scholars derive it from Proto‑Indo‑European *ǵʰerk(ʷ)- ‘fork’ (though the development of the -c- is problematic), while others connect it to a stem *furkaz (from *perg-) ‘stake, pole’, which would relate it to words for bolts, bars, and staffs.",
    "origin_language": "Proto-Indo-European",
    "root_words": [
      "furca",
      "*furkō",
      "forke",
      "forque",
      "*ǵʰerk(ʷ)-",
      "*furkaz",
      "*perg-"
    ],
    "first_known_use": "Old English, c. 9th–11th century",
