  "facts": [
    "English \"fork\" comes from Old English forca, borrowed from Latin furca; that Latin root also produced the insult furcifer (originally \"one who carries a fork\") and the technical adjective furcate/\"forked.\"",
    "The dining fork was introduced into Western Europe from Byzantine/Italian practice but provoked moral and social resistance—Renaissance and Puritan commentators often ridiculed it as an effeminate, continental affectation, so possession and use of forks long signaled elite taste and confessional identity.",
    "English shows an unusual split: the name of the whole implement is a borrowing (fork), while the native Germanic word survives for its prongs (tine), so a borrowed term labels the object while the inherited word labels a component."
  ]
